In the article quoted below, David is either wrong or lying.  Feel free to
E-mail me if you need details.

In article <strnlghtCwCJs5.Av6@netcom.com>,
David Sternlight <strnlght@netcom.com> wrote:
>In article <9409161407.AA03753@ah.com>, Eric Hughes <hughes@ah.com> wrote:
>>   Can RC4 still be construed as a trade secret or proprirtary to
>>   RSADS and Bizdos or are, as I understand from previous messages,
>>   we free to use RC4 now (ignoring the submarine patent issue)?
>> 
>>A trade secret is just that, a secret.  For parties unrelated to the
>>holder of the secret, once it's no longer a secret, it's not a secret,
>>and the former holder of the secret has no protection at all.  In
>>other words, if you're not, say, a BSAFE licensee, you are free to use
>>the alleged RC4 algorithm.
>> 
>>Let me repeat.  If you've never made an agreement with RSADSI about
>>not distributing their trade secrets, RSADSI has _no_ claim against
>>you about the trade secret.  (I don't know if the name "RC4" is
>>trademarked.)
>
>You may be in error on this. Many companies use trade secret protection in
>preference to patents, and if it were that weak they wouldn't. I suggest you
>check with an experienced attorney in these matters.
>
>To use a parallel, receiving stolen property is a felony even if you weren't
>the thief. I think this is enough of a straw in the wind to require careful
>investigation of your claim, though I don't want to push the parallel so far
>as to claim that the revealed trade secret is stolen property, without an
>attorney's opinion.
>
>> 
>>Note the use of the word 'unrelated' in the sentence above.  The
>>situation is hazier there.  Both licensees and agents (including
>>employees) of the holder of the secret are liable for damages if they
>>breach the trust of the secret holder by revealing the secret.  This
>>liability, however, does _not_ make the secret any less revealed.  The
>>former holder can sue for damages, assuming there's someone to sue and
>>the damages can be ascertained.
>> 
>>If you're the user of a product which includes RC4, like Lotus Notes,
>>for example, the agreement between Lotus and RSADSI about protection
>>of trade secrets doesn't apply to you, assuming you don't work for
>>Lotus or RSADSI.  You weren't a party to the agreement, and its terms
>>don't directly affect thrid parties.  You made a (shrink-wrap)
>>agreement with Lotus, not RSADSI.
>
>But if the agreement between Lotus and RSADSI requires Lotus to pass on the
>trade secret protection agreements (including no reverse engineering) to
>Lotus' customers, then you are still bound by them if Lotus does discharge
>its obligation in, say, their license agreement with you.
>
>Note, by the way, that what had been called shrink-wrap agreements are
>strengthened against claims attacking them by sealing the disks separately,
>with the text of the agreement and the notice that if you don't agree with
>it you're not to open the sealed envelope but instead to return the product
>for a refund. Most such agreements are printed right on that inner envelope.
>Thus it's no longer a "shrink-wrap" agreement since you have the opportunity
>to either accept it or return the disks unopened after you have been given
>the opportunity to become fully familiar with the terms. Since such products
>are licensed, not sold, the license has not changed hands unless you agree
>to the terms, and you acquire no property rights in the product either
>before or after you open the outer shrink-wrap.
>
>David
